[normal]The similarities and differences in patterns of tobacco smuggling in the UK and Ireland, how they affect on each other, and the implications of the restrictions on National Crime Agency[bold] operations in Northern Ireland[bold]&#xa0;[bold]The price of duty-paid tobacco products is 
[normal]not
[normal] the most important factor in determining levels of illicit trade
[normal]. Research shows that 
[normal]other factors – principally sharing a border with certain countries where operating an illicit trade is easier – are what 
[normal]is 
[normal]influenc
[normal]ing
[normal] illicit rates
[normal]  
[normal]The Republic of Ireland has the highest rate of tobacco duty in the EU, followed by the UK
[normal].
[normal]The UK has some of the hig
[normal]hest tobacco taxes in the world, with 
[normal]tax accounting for up to 
[normal]88% of the RRP
[normal] on some brands
[normal]. 
[normal]The fall
[normal]ing rate of the illicit market
[normal] has continued despite rising tobacco taxes and consequent high prices in the same period.
